description: From Middle English tre, tree, treo, treou, trew, trow, from Old English trēo, trēow (“tree, wood, timber, beam, log, stake, stick, grove, cross, rood”), from Proto-West Germanic *treu, from Proto-Germanic *trewą (“tree, wood”), from pre-Germanic *dréwom, thematic e-grade derivative of Proto-Indo-European *dóru (“tree”).

entries.meaning: A perennial woody plant, not exactly defined, but differentiated from a shrub by its larger size (typically over a few meters in height) or growth habit, usually having a single (or few) main axis or trunk unbranched for some distance above the ground and a head of branches and foliage.
examples: Hyperion is the tallest living tree in the world.
Birds have a nest in a tree in the garden.

entries.meaning: Any plant that is reminiscent of the above but not classified as a tree (in any botanical sense).
An object made from a tree trunk and having multiple hooks or storage platforms.
examples: He had the choice of buying a scratching post or a cat tree.

entries.meaning: A device used to hold or stretch a shoe open.
examples: He put a shoe tree in each of his shoes.

entries.meaning: The structural frame of a saddle.
(graph theory) A connected graph with no cycles or, if the graph is finite, equivalently a connected graph with n vertices and n−1 edges.
(computing theory) A recursive data structure in which each node has zero or more nodes as children.
(graphical user interface) A display or listing of entries or elements such that there are primary and secondary entries shown, usually linked by drawn lines or by indenting to the right.
examples: We’ll show it as a tree list.

entries.meaning: Any structure or construct having branches representing divergence or possible choices.
The structure or wooden frame used in the construction of a saddle used in horse riding.
(chemistry) A mass of crystals, aggregated in arborescent forms, obtained by precipitation of a metal from solution.
(uncountable, mathematics) Alternative letter-case form of TREE.

verbs.description: tree (third-person singular simple present trees, present participle treeing, simple past and past participle treed)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To chase (an animal or person) up a tree.

examples: Black bears can tree their cubs for protection, but grizzly bears cannot.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To place upon a tree; to fit with a tree; to stretch upon a tree.
(intransitive) To take refuge in a tree.
